<h2>Overview — why this partner is useful</h2>
<p>The strongest case for resilience and equity is easy to nod along to and then quietly ignore when the numbers favour building. This partner makes that case hard to ignore. It will ask who your redesign displaces, whether your green-blue claims hold up against flood and heat data, and whether your affordability story is real. The point is not to obey it any more than you obey the Urban Planner. The point is to <strong>synthesise the two</strong> and name the trade-off you can actually defend in public.</p>
<p>Like every partner in this course, it can be <strong>confidently wrong about quantitative claims</strong> (flood depths, displacement counts, cost of green infrastructure). Catching a specific wrong number is exactly the "one thing the AI got wrong" move your <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation</a> needs.</p>

<h2>Pairs with</h2>
<p><strong><a href="/ai-partners/urban-planner/">The Urban Planner</a></strong> — the deliberate counterweight. Run both. The two partners disagree on purpose, and your Sustainable Neighbourhood Plan is the synthesis you can stand behind in front of a real audience.</p>

